I don't really know if Capcom used MIDI minus a constant. In my sound engine, I only have notes C to B, and to do other note I have to do octave change commands. I know some commercial games did it that way too. This can allow you to code the note in one nybble and the lenght in another so that it takes up less space than having note in one byte and lenght in another byte, altough you'll have to add octave changes frequently, and sometimes even very frequently.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Sat Jan 17, 2009 2:36 pm</p><hr />
